For each FDC percentile (e.g., Q??, Q??), a model was fitted of the form: \\[
Q_{\\%} = a + b(\\Delta P) + \\frac{Y}{1 + \\exp\\left( \\frac{T - T_{\\mathrm{half}}}{S} \\right)}
\\] where \(Q_{\\%}\) is the flow percentile, \(\\Delta P\) is deviation of annual rainfall from the long-term mean, \(T\) is plantation age (years), \(Y\) is the magnitude of flow reduction due to afforestation, \(T_{\\mathrm{half}}\) is the time (years) at which half the total reduction occurs, and \(S\) controls the sigmoidal shape. The rainfall term \(b(\\Delta P)\) captures climate variability, while the sigmoidal term models increasing ET as the plantation matures. Under average climate conditions (\(\\Delta P = 0\)), the equilibrium post-afforestation flow is \(a\), and the pre-treatment flow approximates \(a + Y\). A similar inverse sigmoidal model was used for zero-flow days (\(N_{\\mathrm{zero}}\)).

An additional model quantified afforestationˇŻs impact on stream intermittency by analyzing zero-flow days (\(N_{\\mathrm{zero}}\)). Applied to Group 1 catchments (Stewarts Creek, Pine Creek, Redhill), it used an inverse sigmoidal form: \\[
N_{\\mathrm{zero}} = a + b(\\Delta P) + \\frac{Y}{1 + \\exp\\left( \\frac{T - T_{\\mathrm{half}}}{S} \\right)}
\\] where \(Y > 0\) indicates increased zero days with plantation age. The model performed exceptionally well (E = 0.95¨C0.99) and both rainfall and time terms were significant (p < 0.05). Climate-adjusted results show dramatic increases: by year 8, Stewarts and Pine Creeks flow less than 50% of the time; Redhill shifts from near-permanent to highly intermittent flow by year 11. This confirms that afforestation in small, low-storage catchments can drastically alter flow regime continuity, with implications for aquatic ecosystems and water supply reliability.
